 sounds.%0a> %0a> The results of the study indicate that after the 3-week phonetic training program, the speakers improved the vowel sounds /i/ and /ʌ/ and the consonants /b/, /v/ and /d/. However, no significant improvements were found for the sounds: /ɪ/, /æ/ and /ð/. As Bella said in her previous post, /ð/ is a sound that is non-existent in Catalan-spanish, but it is found in the English language. Therefore, it is not shocking that L2 speakers had a challenging time improving their pronunciation of this sound. I found it interesting that L2 speakers were able to improve their pronunciation of multiple vowel sounds as I believe that those sounds are more difficult to master.%0a> %0a> Source:%0a> Carlet, A., & Cebrian, J. (2014). Training Catalan Speakers to Identify L2 Consonants and Vowels: A Short-Term High Variability Training Study. Retrieved February 27, 2021, from http://doe.concordia.ca/copal/documents/8_Carlet_Cebrian_Vol5.pdf%0a
